    19	Q: Why does Partition Resizer move all the data around my disk?
    20	A: This is done for two reasons. Indeed, moving the data is not necessary
    21	for shrinking a partition. But leaving the data in it's original place,
    22	results in unused sectors in the partition's FAT, which is lost space. The
    23	second reason is that you cannot grow a partition without growing it's FAT,
    24	and in order to grow the FAT, you have to move the data.
    25	
    26	Q: Why is it that the program shouldn't be run from the working partition, and
    27	why the hell doesn't your program check this?
    28	A: When working, the program writes some data in a file. This file is 
    29	overwritten and deleted when the work is over. But after the data moving,
    30	DOS doesn't know there are changes, so it tries to write the data back to the
    31	old position of the file. Worse, when the file is deleted, DOS changes the 
    32	old sectors of FAT, which can be any sector in the disk. You understand of
    33	course, that these random writes on the disk can be a dissaster to your data. 
    34	Apart from that, the resque file is not deleted properly, so the program 
    35	will find it again the next time it runs, and will falsely ask you to continue
    36	an unfinished work. You don't want to know what will happen to your data if
    37	you do the same resizing process twice... As for checking the drive from 
    38	which the program is running, it's fairly impossible, since it could be run
    39	from a compressed drive that resides in the working partition, which has the 
    40	same results.
    41	
    42	Q: Is Partition Resizer compatible with drive compression software (like
    43	Doublespace or Stacker)?
    44	A: The program itself works fine with these, since it doesn't consider them
    45	as drives. Partition Resizer scans ONLY physical drives for partitions.
    46	But it shouldn't be run from a compressed drive that resides in a partition
    47	that will be resized or moved. If you're uncertain about that, just run
    48	Partition Resizer from a bootable floppy disk.
    49	
    50	Q: Why isn't there an undo option?
    51	A: There's no need for that. All actions done by Partition Resizer can be
    52	undone easily by doing the opposite thing from what we want to undo, p.e.
    53	growing undoes shrinking.
