    55	Q: Partition Resizer shows 3 partitions in my disk, while I've got 2. Is the
    56	program going nuts, or is it me the one who needs therapy?
    57	A: Neither. The third partition shown is an extended partition, a structure
    58	in the partition table that holds logical drives. Since one of your partitions
    59	is a logical drive, it needs an extended partition to contain it. For more
    60	information, check the 3rd section of PRESIZER.DOC file to see some detailed
    61	explaination of the partition structure. 
    62	
    63	Q: Why can't I shrink my extended partition?
    64	A: It's pretty possible that you have made a common mistake: The extended
    65	partition is not a data partition. What you might want to resize is a logical
    66	drive inside the extended partition. Extended partitions are not DOS drives,
    67	they're just structures that hold logical drives inside them. If you want
    68	to make more space for a new drive, then you'll have to resize a logical drive
    69	and not the extended partition. You will only need to resize the extended 
    70	partition if you have resized or deleted a primary partition, and you want
    71	to use this space inside the extended partition, or if you just shrunk or 
    72	deleted a logical drive, and you want to use the space created for growing
    73	or creating a primary partition. Just read section 3 of PRESIZER.DOC for 
    74	details.
    75	
    76	Q: Can I change a partition's cluster size with Partition Resizer, and keep
    77	my data?
    78	A: Yes. You have to make a little empty space in the drive by shrinking the
    79	original partition, and then create a small partition and start moving your 
    80	data in it, while shrinking the old partition and growing the new one. When 
    81	all the data is in the new partition, change the old partition's cluster size, 
    82	and move the data back to the old partition using the same technique. This 
    83	process might take a bit long, since there's a lot of moving and resizing in 
    84	it. But the whole thing is much faster if you have enough empty space in the 
    85	original partition. I haven't heard of a cluster changing program yet, and I'm 
    86	not planning to write one in the near future. So, you'll have to put up with 
    87	this solution, since there's no other known way of changing a partition's 
    88	cluster size without loosing the data in it.
